# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: relation-extraction
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] In linguistics, **coreference**, sometimes written **co-reference**, occurs when two or more expressions refer to the same person or thing; they have the same referent.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] For example, in *Bill said Alice would arrive soon, and she did*, the words *Alice* and *she* refer to the same person.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] Co-reference is often non-trivial to determine.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] For example, in *Bill said he would come*, the word *he* may or may not refer to Bill.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] Linguists commonly use indices to notate coreference, as in *Billi said hei would come*.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] Such expressions are said to be *coindexed*, indicating that they should be interpreted as coreferential.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] When expressions are coreferential, the first to occur is often a full or descriptive form (for example, an entire personal name, perhaps with a title and role), while later occurrences use shorter forms (for example, just a given name, surname, or pronoun).
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] The earlier occurrence is known as the antecedent and the other is called a proform, anaphor, or reference.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] However, pronouns can sometimes refer forward, as in "When she arrived home, Alice went to sleep." In such cases, the coreference is called cataphoric rather than anaphoric.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] Coreference is important for binding phenomena in the field of syntax.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] The theory of binding explores the syntactic relationship that exists between coreferential expressions in sentences and texts.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] When exploring coreference, numerous distinctions can be made, e.g. anaphora, cataphora, split antecedents, coreferring noun phrases, etc.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] follows the expression to which it refers (its antecedent).
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] precedes the expression to which it refers (its postcedent).
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] – Coreferring noun phrases, whereby the second noun phrase is a predication over the first.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] Semanticists and logicians sometimes draw a distinction between coreference and what is known as a bound variable.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] Bound variables occur when the antecedent to the proform is an indefinite quantified expression, e.g.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] Quantified expressions such as *every student* and *no student* are not considered referential.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] These expressions are grammatically singular but do not pick out single referents in the discourse or real world.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] Thus, the antecedents to *his* in these examples are not properly referential, and neither is *his*.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] Instead, it is considered a *variable* that is *bound* by its antecedent.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] Its reference varies based upon which of the students in the discourse world is thought of.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] It can mean that Jack likes his grade but everyone else dislikes Jack's grade; or that no one likes their **own** grade except Jack.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] In the first meaning, *his* is coreferential; in the second, it is a bound variable because its reference varies over the set of all students.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] Coindex notation is commonly used for both cases.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] That is, when two or more expressions are coindexed, it does not signal whether one is dealing with coreference or a bound variable (or as in the last example, whether it depends on interpretation).
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] In computational linguistics, coreference resolution is a well-studied problem in discourse.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] To derive the correct interpretation of a text, or even to estimate the relative importance of various mentioned subjects, pronouns and other referring expressions must be connected to the right individuals.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] Algorithms intended to resolve coreferences commonly look first for the nearest preceding individual that is compatible with the referring expression.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] For example, *she* might attach to a preceding expression such as *the woman* or *Anne*, but not as probably to *Bill*.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] Pronouns such as *himself* have much stricter constraints.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] As with many linguistic tasks, there is a tradeoff between precision and recall.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] Cluster-quality metrics commonly used to evaluate coreference resolution algorithms include the Rand index, the adjusted Rand index, and different mutual information-based methods.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] A particular problem for coreference resolution in English is the pronoun *it*, which has many uses.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] *It* can refer much like *he* and *she*, except that it generally refers to inanimate objects (the rules are actually more complex: animals may be any of *it*, *he*, or *she*; ships are traditionally *she*; hurricanes are usually *it* despite having gendered names).
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] *It* can also refer to abstractions rather than beings, e.g.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] Sometimes **it'**s the loudest who have the most influence.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] Pleonastic uses are not considered referential, and so are not part of coreference.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] Approaches to coreference resolution can broadly be separated into mention-pair, mention-ranking or entity-based algorithms.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] Mention-pair algorithms involve binary decisions if a pair of two given mentions belong to the same entity.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] Entity-wide constraints like gender are not considered, which leads to error propagation.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] For example, the pronouns *he* or *she* can both have a high probability of coreference with *the teacher*, but cannot be coreferent with each other.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] Mention-ranking algorithms expand on this idea but instead stipulate that one mention can only be coreferent with one (previous) mention.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] As a result, each previous mention must be given a score and the highest scoring mention (or no mention) is linked.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] Finally, in entity-based methods mentions are linked based on information of the whole coreference chain instead of individual mentions.
[src:relation-extraction/coreference-resolution] The representation of a variable-width chain is more complex and computationally expensive than mention-based methods, which lead to these algorithms being mostly based on neural network architectures.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The notion of dependencies between grammatical units has existed since the earliest recorded grammars, e.g.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Pāṇini, and the dependency concept therefore arguably predates that of phrase structure by many centuries.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Ibn Maḍāʾ, a 12th-century linguist from Córdoba, Andalusia, may have been the first grammarian to use the term *dependency* in the grammatical sense that we use it today.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] In early modern times, the dependency concept seems to have coexisted side by side with that of phrase structure, the latter having entered Latin, French, English and other grammars from the widespread study of term logic of antiquity.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Dependency is also concretely present in the works of Sámuel Brassai (1800–1897), a Hungarian linguist, Franz Kern (1830–1894), a German philologist, and of Heimann Hariton Tiktin (1850–1936), a Romanian linguist.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Modern dependency grammars, however, begin primarily with the work of Lucien Tesnière.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Tesnière was a Frenchman, a polyglot, and a professor of linguistics at the universities in Strasbourg and Montpellier.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] His major work *Éléments de syntaxe structurale* was published posthumously in 1959 – he died in 1954.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The basic approach to syntax he developed has at least partially influenced the work of others in the 1960s, although it is not clear in what way these works were inspired by other sources.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] A number of other dependency-based grammars have gained prominence since those early works.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] DG has generated a lot of interest in Germany in both theoretical syntax and language pedagogy.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] In recent years, the great development surrounding dependency-based theories has come from computational linguistics and is due, in part, to the influential work that David Hays did in machine translation at the RAND Corporation in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Dependency-based systems are increasingly being used to parse natural language and generate tree banks.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Interest in dependency grammar is growing at present, international conferences on dependency linguistics being a relatively recent development (Depling 2011, Depling 2013, Depling 2015, Depling 2017, Depling 2019 Archived 2019-03-06 at the Wayback Machine).
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Dependency is a one-to-one correspondence: for every element (e.g. word or morph) in the sentence, there is exactly one node in the structure of that sentence that corresponds to that element.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The result of this one-to-one correspondence is that dependency grammars are word (or morph) grammars.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] All that exist are the elements and the dependencies that connect the elements into a structure.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] This situation should be compared with phrase structure.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Phrase structure is a one-to-one-or-more correspondence, which means that, for every element in a sentence, there are one or more nodes in the structure that correspond to that element.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The result of this difference is that dependency structures are minimal compared to their phrase structure counterparts, since they tend to contain many fewer nodes.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] These trees illustrate two possible ways to render the dependency and phrase structure relations (see below).
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] This dependency tree is an "ordered" tree, i.e. it reflects actual word order.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Many dependency trees abstract away from linear order and focus just on hierarchical order, which means they do not show actual word order.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] This constituency (= phrase structure) tree follows the conventions of bare phrase structure (BPS), whereby the words themselves are employed as the node labels.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The distinction between dependency and phrase structure grammars derives in large part from the initial division of the clause.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The phrase structure relation derives from an initial binary division, whereby the clause is split into a subject noun phrase (NP) and a predicate verb phrase (VP).
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] This division is certainly present in the basic analysis of the clause that we find in the works of, for instance, Leonard Bloomfield and Noam Chomsky.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Tesnière, however, argued vehemently against this binary division, preferring instead to position the verb as the root of all clause structure.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Tesnière's stance was that the subject-predicate division stems from term logic and has no place in linguistics.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Link grammar is similar to dependency grammar, but link grammar does not include directionality between the linked words, and thus does not describe head-dependent relationships.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Hybrid dependency/phrase structure grammar uses dependencies between words, but also includes dependencies between phrasal nodes – see for example the Quranic Arabic Dependency Treebank.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The derivation trees of tree-adjoining grammar are dependency structures, although the full trees of TAG rendered in terms of phrase structure, so in this regard, it is not clear whether TAG should be viewed more as a dependency or phrase structure grammar.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] There are major differences between the grammars just listed.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] In this regard, the dependency relation is compatible with other major tenets of theories of grammar.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Thus like phrase structure grammars, dependency grammars can be mono- or multistratal, representational or derivational, construction- or rule-based.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] There are various conventions that DGs employ to represent dependencies.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The representations in (a–d) are trees, whereby the specific conventions employed in each tree vary.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Solid lines are *dependency edges* and lightly dotted lines are *projection lines*.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The only difference between tree (a) and tree (b) is that tree (a) employs the category class to label the nodes whereas tree (b) employs the words themselves as the node labels.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Tree (c) is a reduced tree insofar as the string of words below and projection lines are deemed unnecessary and are hence omitted.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Tree (d) abstracts away from linear order and reflects just hierarchical order.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The arrow arcs in (e) are an alternative convention used to show dependencies and are favored by Word Grammar.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The brackets in (f) are seldom used, but are nevertheless quite capable of reflecting the dependency hierarchy; dependents appear enclosed in more brackets than their heads.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] And finally, the indentations like those in (g) are another convention that is sometimes employed to indicate the hierarchy of words.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Dependents are placed underneath their heads and indented.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Like tree (d), the indentations in (g) abstract away from linear order.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The point to these conventions is that they are just that, namely conventions.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] They do not influence the basic commitment to dependency as the relation that is grouping syntactic units.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The dependency representations above (and further below) show syntactic dependencies.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Indeed, most work in dependency grammar focuses on syntactic dependencies.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Syntactic dependencies are, however, just one of three or four types of dependencies.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Meaning–text theory, for instance, emphasizes the role of semantic and morphological dependencies in addition to syntactic dependencies.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] A fourth type, prosodic dependencies, can also be acknowledged.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Distinguishing between these types of dependencies can be important, in part because if one fails to do so, the likelihood that semantic, morphological, and/or prosodic dependencies will be mistaken for syntactic dependencies is great.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The following four subsections briefly sketch each of these dependency types.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] During the discussion, the existence of syntactic dependencies is taken for granted and used as an orientation point for establishing the nature of the other three dependency types.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Semantic dependencies are understood in terms of predicates and their arguments.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The arguments of a predicate are semantically dependent on that predicate.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Often, semantic dependencies overlap with and point in the same direction as syntactic dependencies.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] At times, however, semantic dependencies can point in the opposite direction of syntactic dependencies, or they can be entirely independent of syntactic dependencies.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The two arguments *Sam* and *Sally* in tree (a) are dependent on the predicate *likes*, whereby these arguments are also syntactically dependent on *likes*.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] What this means is that the semantic and syntactic dependencies overlap and point in the same direction (down the tree).
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Attributive adjectives, however, are predicates that take their head noun as their argument, hence *big* is a predicate in tree (b) that takes *bones* as its one argument; the semantic dependency points up the tree and therefore runs counter to the syntactic dependency.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] A similar situation obtains in (c), where the preposition predicate *on* takes the two arguments *the picture* and *the wall*; one of these semantic dependencies points up the syntactic hierarchy, whereas the other points down it.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Finally, the predicate *to help* in (d) takes the one argument *Jim* but is not directly connected to *Jim* in the syntactic hierarchy, which means that semantic dependency is entirely independent of the syntactic dependencies.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Morphological dependencies obtain between words or parts of words.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] When a given word or part of a word influences the form of another word, then the latter is morphologically dependent on the former.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Agreement and concord are therefore manifestations of morphological dependencies.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Like semantic dependencies, morphological dependencies can overlap with and point in the same direction as syntactic dependencies, overlap with and point in the opposite direction of syntactic dependencies, or be entirely independent of syntactic dependencies.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The arrows are now used to indicate morphological dependencies.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The plural *houses* in (a) demands the plural of the demonstrative determiner, hence *these* appears, not *this*, which means there is a morphological dependency that points down the hierarchy from *houses* to *these*.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The situation is reversed in (b), where the singular subject *Sam* demands the appearance of the agreement suffix *-s* on the finite verb *works*, which means there is a morphological dependency pointing up the hierarchy from *Sam* to *works*.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The type of determiner in the German examples (c) and (d) influences the inflectional suffix that appears on the adjective *alt*.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] When the indefinite article *ein* is used, the strong masculine ending *-er* appears on the adjective.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] When the definite article *der* is used, in contrast, the weak ending *-e* appears on the adjective.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Thus since the choice of determiner impacts the morphological form of the adjective, there is a morphological dependency pointing from the determiner to the adjective, whereby this morphological dependency is entirely independent of the syntactic dependencies.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The masculine subject *le chien* in (a) demands the masculine form of the predicative adjective *blanc*, whereas the feminine subject *la maison* demands the feminine form of this adjective.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] A morphological dependency that is entirely independent of the syntactic dependencies therefore points again across the syntactic hierarchy.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Morphological dependencies play an important role in typological studies.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Languages are classified as mostly head-marking (*Sam work-s*) or mostly dependent-marking (*these houses*), whereby most if not all languages contain at least some minor measure of both head and dependent marking.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Prosodic dependencies are acknowledged in order to accommodate the behavior of clitics.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] A clitic is a syntactically autonomous element that is prosodically dependent on a host.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] A clitic is therefore integrated into the prosody of its host, meaning that it forms a single word with its host.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Prosodic dependencies exist entirely in the linear dimension (horizontal dimension), whereas standard syntactic dependencies exist in the hierarchical dimension (vertical dimension).
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Classic examples of clitics in English are reduced auxiliaries (e.g.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] A given clitic is often prosodically dependent on its syntactic dependent (*He'll*, *There's*) or on its head (*would've*).
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] At other times, it can depend prosodically on a word that is neither its head nor its immediate dependent (*Florida's*).
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Syntactic dependencies are the focus of most work in DG, as stated above.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] How the presence and the direction of syntactic dependencies are determined is of course often open to debate.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] In this regard, it must be acknowledged that the validity of syntactic dependencies in the trees throughout this article is being taken for granted.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] However, these hierarchies are such that many DGs can largely support them, although there will certainly be points of disagreement.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The basic question about how syntactic dependencies are discerned has proven difficult to answer definitively.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] One should acknowledge in this area, however, that the basic task of identifying and discerning the presence and direction of the syntactic dependencies of DGs is no easier or harder than determining the constituent groupings of phrase structure grammars.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Etymological considerations also provide helpful clues about the direction of dependencies.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] A promising principle upon which to base the existence of syntactic dependencies is distribution.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] When one is striving to identify the root of a given phrase, the word that is most responsible for determining the distribution of that phrase as a whole is its root.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Traditionally, DGs have had a different approach to linear order (word order) than phrase structure grammars.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Dependency structures are minimal compared to their phrase structure counterparts, and these minimal structures allow one to focus intently on the two ordering dimensions.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Separating the vertical dimension (hierarchical order) from the horizontal dimension (linear order) is easily accomplished.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] This aspect of dependency structures has allowed DGs, starting with Tesnière (1959), to focus on hierarchical order in a manner that is hardly possible for phrase structure grammars.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] For Tesnière, linear order was secondary to hierarchical order insofar as hierarchical order preceded linear order in the mind of a speaker.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The stemmas (trees) that Tesnière produced reflected this view; they abstracted away from linear order to focus almost entirely on hierarchical order.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Many DGs that followed Tesnière adopted this practice, that is, they produced tree structures that reflect hierarchical order alone, e.g.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The traditional focus on hierarchical order generated the impression that DGs have little to say about linear order, and it has contributed to the view that DGs are particularly well-suited to examine languages with free word order.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] A negative result of this focus on hierarchical order, however, is that there is a dearth of DG explorations of particular word order phenomena, such as of standard discontinuities.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Comprehensive dependency grammar accounts of topicalization, *wh*-fronting, scrambling, and extraposition are mostly absent from many established DG frameworks.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] This situation can be contrasted with phrase structure grammars, which have devoted tremendous effort to exploring these phenomena.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The nature of the dependency relation does not, however, prevent one from focusing on linear order.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Dependency structures are as capable of exploring word order phenomena as phrase structures.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The following trees illustrate this point; they represent one way of exploring discontinuities using dependency structures.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The trees suggest the manner in which common discontinuities can be addressed.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The a-trees on the left show projectivity violations (= crossing lines), and the b-trees on the right demonstrate one means of addressing these violations.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The displaced constituent takes on a word as its head that is not its governor.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The words in red mark the catena (=chain) of words that extends from the root of the displaced constituent to the governor of that constituent.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Discontinuities are then explored in terms of these catenae.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The limitations on topicalization, *wh*-fronting, scrambling, and extraposition can be explored and identified by examining the nature of the catenae involved.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Traditionally, DGs have treated the syntactic functions (= grammatical functions, grammatical relations) as primitive.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] They posit an inventory of functions (e.g. subject, object, oblique, determiner, attribute, predicative, etc.).
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] These functions can appear as labels on the dependencies in the tree structures, e.g.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The syntactic functions in this tree are shown in green: ATTR (attribute), COMP-P (complement of preposition), COMP-TO (complement of to), DET (determiner), P-ATTR (prepositional attribute), PRED (predicative), SUBJ (subject), TO-COMP (to complement).
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The functions chosen and abbreviations used in the tree here are merely representative of the general stance of DGs toward the syntactic functions.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The actual inventory of functions and designations employed vary from DG to DG.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] As a primitive of the theory, the status of these functions is very different from that in some phrase structure grammars.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Traditionally, phrase structure grammars derive the syntactic functions from the constellation.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] For instance, the object is identified as the NP appearing inside finite VP, and the subject as the NP appearing outside of finite VP.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Since DGs reject the existence of a finite VP constituent, they were never presented with the option to view the syntactic functions in this manner.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] This question about what comes first (the functions or the constellation) is not an inflexible matter.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] The stances of both grammar types (dependency and phrase structure) are not narrowly limited to the traditional views.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Dependency and phrase structure are both fully compatible with both approaches to the syntactic functions.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] Indeed, monostratal systems, that are solely based on dependency or phrase structure, will likely reject the notion that the functions are derived from the constellation or that the constellation is derived from the functions.
[src:relation-extraction/dependency-grammar] They will take both to be primitive, which means neither can be derived from the other.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] In this example, a person name consisting of one token, a two-token company name and a temporal expression have been detected and classified.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] In the expression *named entity*, the word *named* restricts the task to those entities for which one or many strings, such as words or phrases, stand (fairly) consistently for some referent.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] This is closely related to rigid designators, as defined by Saul Kripke, although in practice NER deals with many names and referents that are not philosophically "rigid".
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] For instance, the *automotive company created by Henry Ford in 1903* can be referred to as *Ford* or *Ford Motor Company*, although "Ford" can refer to many other entities as well (see Ford).
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] Full named-entity recognition is often broken down, conceptually and possibly also in implementations, as two distinct problems: detection of names, and classification of the names by the type of entity they refer to (e.g. person, organization, or location).
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] The first phase is typically simplified to a segmentation problem: names are defined to be contiguous spans of tokens, with no nesting, so that "Bank of America" is a single name, disregarding the fact that inside this name, the substring "America" is itself a name.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] This segmentation problem is formally similar to chunking.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] The second phase requires choosing an ontology by which to organize categories of things.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] Temporal expressions and some numerical expressions (e.g., money, percentages, etc.) may also be considered as named entities in the context of the NER task.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] While some instances of these types are good examples of rigid designators (e.g., the year 2001) there are also many invalid ones (e.g., I take my vacations in “June”).
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] In the first case, the year *2001* refers to the *2001st year of the Gregorian calendar*.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] In the second case, the month *June* may refer to the month of an undefined year (*past June*, *next June*, *every June*, etc.).
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] It is arguable that the definition of *named entity* is loosened in such cases for practical reasons.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] The definition of the term *named entity* is therefore not strict and often has to be explained in the context in which it is used.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] Certain hierarchies of named entity types have been proposed in the literature.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] BBN categories, proposed in 2002, are used for *question answering* and consists of 29 types and 64 subtypes.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] Sekine's extended hierarchy, proposed in 2002, is made of 200 subtypes.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] More recently, in 2011 Ritter used a hierarchy based on common Freebase entity types in ground-breaking experiments on NER over social media text.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] NER can have reference resolution ambiguities where the same name can refer to different entities of the same type.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] For example, "JFK" can refer to the former president of the United States or his son.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] The same name can refer to completely different types.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] "JFK" might refer to the airport in New York.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] "IRA" can refer to Individual Retirement Account, International Reading Association or Irish Republican Army.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] For example, "The White House" can refer to an organization instead of a location.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] To evaluate the quality of an NER system's output, several measures have been defined.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] The usual measures are called precision, recall, and F1 score.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] However, several issues remain in just how to calculate those values.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] These statistical measures work reasonably well for the obvious cases of finding or missing a real entity exactly; and for finding a non-entity.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] However, NER can fail in many other ways, many of which are arguably "partially correct", and should not be counted as complete success or failures.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] One overly simple method of measuring accuracy is merely to count what fraction of all tokens in the text were correctly or incorrectly identified as part of entity references (or as being entities of the correct type).
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] It follows from the above definition that any prediction that misses a single token, includes a spurious token, or has the wrong class, is a hard error and does not contribute positively to either precision or recall.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] Thus, this measure may be said to be pessimistic: it can be the case that many "errors" are close to correct, and might be adequate for a given purpose.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] For example, one system might always omit titles such as "Ms." or "Ph.D.", but be compared to a system or ground-truth data that expects titles to be included.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] In that case, every such name is treated as an error.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] Because of such issues, it is important actually to examine the kinds of errors, and decide how important they are given one's goals and requirements.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] Evaluation models based on a token-by-token matching have been proposed.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] Such models may be given partial credit for overlapping matches (such as using the Intersection over Union criterion).
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] They allow a finer grained evaluation and comparison of extraction systems.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] NER systems have been created that use linguistic grammar-based techniques as well as statistical models such as machine learning.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] State of the art systems may incorporate multiple approaches.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] Hand-crafted grammar-based systems typically obtain better precision, but at the cost of lower recall and months of work by experienced computational linguists.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] Statistical NER systems typically require a large amount of manually annotated training data.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] Semisupervised approaches have been suggested to avoid part of the annotation effort.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] In the statistical learning era, NER was usually performed by learning a simple linear regression model on engineered features, then decoded by a bidirectional Viterbi algorithm.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] A **gazetteer** is a list of names and their types, such as "General Electric".
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] It can be used to augment any system for NER.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] They had been often used in the era of statistical machine learning.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] Many different classifier types have been used to perform machine-learned NER, with conditional random fields being a typical choice.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] Transformers features token classification using deep learning models.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] Early work in NER systems in the 1990s was aimed primarily at extraction from journalistic articles.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] Attention then turned to processing of military dispatches and reports.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] Later stages of the automatic content extraction (ACE) evaluation also included several types of informal text styles, such as weblogs and text transcripts from conversational telephone speech conversations.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] Since about 1998, there has been a great deal of interest in entity identification in the molecular biology, bioinformatics, and medical natural language processing communities.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] The most common entity of interest in that domain has been names of genes and gene products.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] There has been also considerable interest in the recognition of chemical entities and drugs in the context of the CHEMDNER competition, with 27 teams participating in this task.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] In 2001, research indicated that even state-of-the-art NER systems were brittle, meaning that NER systems developed for one domain did not typically perform well on other domains.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] Considerable effort is involved in tuning NER systems to perform well in a new domain; this is true for both rule-based and trainable statistical systems.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] As of 2007, state-of-the-art NER systems for English produce near-human performance.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] For example, the best system entering MUC-7 scored 93.39% of F-measure while human annotators scored 97.60% and 96.95%.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] Despite high F1 numbers reported on the MUC-7 dataset, the problem of named-entity recognition is far from being solved.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] The main efforts are directed to reducing the annotations labor by employing semi-supervised learning, robust performance across domains and scaling up to fine-grained entity types.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] In recent years, many projects have turned to crowdsourcing, which is a promising solution to obtain high-quality aggregate human judgments for supervised and semi-supervised machine learning approaches to NER.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] Another challenging task is devising models to deal with linguistically complex contexts such as Twitter and search queries.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] There are some researchers who did some comparisons about the NER performances from different statistical models such as HMM (hidden Markov model), ME (maximum entropy), and CRF (conditional random fields), and feature sets.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] And some researchers recently proposed graph-based semi-supervised learning model for language specific NER tasks.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] A recently emerging task of identifying "important expressions" in text and cross-linking them to Wikipedia can be seen as an instance of extremely fine-grained named-entity recognition, where the types are the actual Wikipedia pages describing the (potentially ambiguous) concepts.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] Another field that has seen progress but remains challenging is the application of NER to Twitter and other microblogs, considered "noisy" due to non-standard orthography, shortness and informality of texts.
[src:relation-extraction/named-entity-recognition] NER challenges in English Tweets have been organized by research communities to compare performances of various approaches, such as bidirectional LSTMs, Learning-to-Search, or CRFs.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] Major processing tasks in an NLP system include: speech recognition, text classification, natural language understanding, and natural language generation.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] Natural language processing has its roots in the 1950s.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] Already in 1950, Alan Turing published an article titled "Computing Machinery and Intelligence," which proposed what is now called the Turing test as a criterion of intelligence, though at the time that was not articulated as a problem separate from artificial intelligence.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] The proposed test includes a task that involves the automated interpretation and generation of natural language.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] Up until the 1980s, most natural language processing systems were based on complex sets of hand-written rules.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] Starting in the late 1980s, however, there was a revolution in natural language processing with the introduction of machine learning algorithms for language processing.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] Symbolic approach, i.e., the hand-coding of a set of rules for manipulating symbols, coupled with a dictionary lookup, was historically the first approach used both by AI in general and by NLP in particular: such as by writing grammars or devising heuristic rules for stemming.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] In the late 1980s and mid-1990s, the statistical approach ended a period of AI winter, which was caused by the inefficiencies of the rule-based approaches.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] The earliest decision trees, producing systems of hard if–then rules, were still very similar to the old rule-based approaches.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] Only the introduction of hidden Markov models, applied to part-of-speech tagging, announced the end of the old rule-based approach.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] A major drawback of statistical methods is that they require elaborate feature engineering.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] Since 2015, neural network–based methods have increasingly replaced traditional statistical approaches, using semantic networks and word embeddings to capture semantic properties of words.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] Intermediate tasks (e.g., part-of-speech tagging and dependency parsing) are not needed anymore.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] Neural machine translation, based on the then-newly invented sequence-to-sequence transformations, made obsolete the intermediate steps, such as word alignment, previously necessary for statistical machine translation.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] The following is a list of some of the most commonly researched tasks in natural language processing.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] Some of these tasks have direct real-world applications, while others more commonly serve as subtasks that are used to aid in solving larger tasks.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] Though natural language processing tasks are closely intertwined, they can be subdivided into categories for convenience.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] Given an image representing printed text, determine the corresponding text.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] Given a sound clip of a person or people speaking, determine the textual representation of the speech.
