[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] Based on long-standing trends in the field, it is possible to extrapolate future directions of NLP.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] Most higher-level NLP applications involve aspects that emulate intelligent behavior and apparent comprehension of natural language.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] More broadly speaking, the technical operationalization of increasingly advanced aspects of cognitive behavior represents one of the developmental trajectories of NLP(see trends among CoNLL shared tasks above).
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] Cognition refers to "the mental action or process of acquiring knowledge and understanding through thought, experience, and the senses." Cognitive science is the interdisciplinary, scientific study of the mind and its processes.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] Cognitive linguistics is an interdisciplinary branch of linguistics, combining knowledge and research from both psychology and linguistics.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] Especially during the age of symbolic NLP, the area of computational linguistics maintained strong ties with cognitive studies.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] Assign relative measures of meaning to a word, phrase, sentence or piece of text based on the information presented before and after the piece of text being analyzed, e.g., by means of a probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG).
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] Ties with cognitive linguistics are part of the historical heritage of NLP, but they have been less frequently addressed since the statistical turn during the 1990s.
[src:relation-extraction/natural-language-processing] More recently, ideas of cognitive NLP have been revived as an approach to achieve explainability, e.g., under the notion of "cognitive AI".
[src:relation-extraction/relationship-extraction] A **relationship extraction** task requires the detection and classification of semantic relationship mentions within a set of artifacts, typically from text or XML documents.
[src:relation-extraction/relationship-extraction] The task is very similar to that of information extraction (IE), but IE additionally requires the removal of repeated relations (disambiguation) and generally refers to the extraction of many different relationships.
[src:relation-extraction/relationship-extraction] The concept of relationship extraction was first introduced during the 7th Message Understanding Conference in 1998.
[src:relation-extraction/relationship-extraction] Relationship extraction involves the identification of relations between entities and it usually focuses on the extraction of binary relations.
[src:relation-extraction/relationship-extraction] Application domains where relationship extraction is useful include gene-disease relationships, protein-protein interaction etc.
[src:relation-extraction/relationship-extraction] Current relationship extraction studies use machine learning technologies, which approach relationship extraction as a classification problem.
[src:relation-extraction/relationship-extraction] Never-Ending Language Learning is a semantic machine learning system developed by a research team at Carnegie Mellon University that extracts relationships from the open web.
[src:relation-extraction/relationship-extraction] There are several methods used to extract relationships and these include text-based relationship extraction.
[src:relation-extraction/relationship-extraction] These methods rely on the use of pretrained relationship structure information or it could entail the learning of the structure in order to reveal relationships.
[src:relation-extraction/relationship-extraction] Another approach to this problem involves the use of domain ontologies.
[src:relation-extraction/relationship-extraction] There is also the approach that involves visual detection of meaningful relationships in parametric values of objects listed on a data table that shift positions as the table is permuted automatically as controlled by the software user.
[src:relation-extraction/relationship-extraction] The poor coverage, rarity and development cost related to structured resources such as semantic lexicons (e.g.
[src:relation-extraction/relationship-extraction] WordNet, UMLS) and domain ontologies (e.g. the Gene Ontology) has given rise to new approaches based on broad, dynamic background knowledge on the Web.
[src:relation-extraction/relationship-extraction] For instance, the ARCHILES technique uses only Wikipedia and search engine page count for acquiring coarse-grained relations to construct lightweight ontologies.
[src:relation-extraction/relationship-extraction] The relationships can be represented using a variety of formalisms/languages.
[src:relation-extraction/relationship-extraction] One such representation language for data on the Web is RDF.
[src:relation-extraction/relationship-extraction] More recently, end-to-end systems which jointly learn to extract entity mentions and their semantic relations have been proposed with strong potential to obtain high performance.
[src:relation-extraction/relationship-extraction] Most of the reported systems have demonstrated their approach on English datasets.
[src:relation-extraction/relationship-extraction] However, data and systems have been described for other languages, e.g., Russian and Vietnamese.
[src:relation-extraction/relationship-extraction] Researchers have constructed multiple datasets for benchmarking relationship extraction methods.
[src:relation-extraction/relationship-extraction] One such dataset was the document-level relationship extraction dataset called DocRED released in 2019.
[src:relation-extraction/relationship-extraction] It uses relations from Wikidata and text from the English Wikipedia.
[src:relation-extraction/relationship-extraction] The dataset has been used by other researchers and a prediction competition has been setup at CodaLab.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] When classification is performed by a computer, statistical methods are normally used to develop the algorithm.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] Often, the individual observations are analyzed into a set of quantifiable properties, known variously as explanatory variables or *features*.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] These properties may variously be categorical (e.g.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] "large", "medium" or "small"), integer-valued (e.g. the number of occurrences of a particular word in an email) or real-valued (e.g. a measurement of blood pressure).
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] Other classifiers work by comparing observations to previous observations by means of a similarity or distance function.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] An algorithm that implements classification, especially in a concrete implementation, is known as a **classifier**.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] The term "classifier" sometimes also refers to the mathematical function, implemented by a classification algorithm, that maps input data to a category.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] Terminology across fields is quite varied.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] In machine learning, the observations are often known as *instances*, the explanatory variables are termed *features* (grouped into a feature vector), and the possible categories to be predicted are *classes*.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] Other fields may use different terminology: e.g. in community ecology, the term "classification" normally refers to cluster analysis.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] Classification and clustering are examples of the more general problem of pattern recognition, which is the assignment of some sort of output value to a given input value.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] A common subclass of classification is probabilistic classification.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] Algorithms of this nature use statistical inference to find the best class for a given instance.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] Unlike other algorithms, which simply output a "best" class, probabilistic algorithms output a probability of the instance being a member of each of the possible classes.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] The best class is normally then selected as the one with the highest probability.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] Early work on statistical classification was undertaken by Fisher, in the context of two-group problems, leading to Fisher's linear discriminant function as the rule for assigning a group to a new observation.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] This early work assumed that data-values within each of the two groups had a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] The extension of this same context to more than two groups has also been considered with a restriction imposed that the classification rule should be linear.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] Unlike frequentist procedures, Bayesian classification procedures provide a natural way of taking into account any available information about the relative sizes of the different groups within the overall population.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] Bayesian procedures tend to be computationally expensive and, in the days before Markov chain Monte Carlo computations were developed, approximations for Bayesian clustering rules were devised.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] Some Bayesian procedures involve the calculation of group-membership probabilities: these provide a more informative outcome than a simple attribution of a single group-label to each new observation.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] Classification can be thought of as two separate problems – binary classification and multiclass classification.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] In binary classification, a better understood task, only two classes are involved, whereas multiclass classification involves assigning an object to one of several classes.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] Since many classification methods have been developed specifically for binary classification, multiclass classification often requires the combined use of multiple binary classifiers.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] Most algorithms describe an individual instance whose category is to be predicted using a feature vector of individual, measurable properties of the instance.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] Each property is termed a feature, also known in statistics as an explanatory variable (or independent variable, although features may or may not be statistically independent).
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] "large", "medium" or "small"); integer-valued (e.g. the number of occurrences of a particular word in an email); or real-valued (e.g. a measurement of blood pressure).
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] If the instance is an image, the feature values might correspond to the pixels of an image; if the instance is a piece of text, the feature values might be occurrence frequencies of different words.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] Some algorithms work only in terms of discrete data and require that real-valued or integer-valued data be *discretized* into groups (e.g. less than 5, between 5 and 10, or greater than 10).
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] A large number of algorithms for classification can be phrased in terms of a linear function that assigns a score to each possible category *k* by combining the feature vector of an instance with a vector of weights, using a dot product.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] The predicted category is the one with the highest score.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] In discrete choice theory, where instances represent people and categories represent choices, the score is considered the utility associated with person *i* choosing category *k*.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] Algorithms with this basic setup are known as linear classifiers.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] What distinguishes them is the procedure for determining (training) the optimal weights/coefficients and the way that the score is interpreted.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] Since no single form of classification is appropriate for all data sets, a large toolkit of classification algorithms has been developed.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] Choices between different possible algorithms are frequently made on the basis of quantitative evaluation of accuracy.
[src:relation-extraction/statistical-classification] In some of these, it is employed as a data mining procedure, while in others more detailed statistical modeling is undertaken.
